1.Data Cleaning

1.1 Reading the Data

  • First, we read the dataset into R:
library(readxl)
box <- read_excel("Box Dataset.xlsx",skip=1,col_names = TRUE,col_types = 
                    c(rep("numeric",8),"date","numeric","text","text",rep("numeric",8),
                      "text","numeric","numeric",rep("text",3),"numeric","numeric",rep("text",31)))

We had to specify the attribute types when reading the data, otherwise the read_excel formula would mess up things and read every column as datatype “logical” (TRUE/FALSE).  

1.2 Some Preliminary Cleaning

  • Then, we would like to eliminate the columns that are useless to modeling. These columns include columns that are all blank and attributes that describe identification codes. We would also like to delete the variables that are calculated from other variables. For example Length/Depth is just box length devided by box depth. We omitted these variables derrived from other variables to avoid multicollinearity.
library(dplyr)
box <- box %>% select_if(~!all(is.na(.)))
box <- box %>% select(-c(`Order #`,`Spec #`,`Customer Code`,`Fold Length`,`Length/Depth`,`Square Footage per piece`))
  • Since ‘Machine’ describes which machine was used to make the boxes, it should be a categorical variable. In addition, we transformed all categorical varibales into factors. Because Batavia wants us to evaluate the factors that relate to the manufacturing cost differential between the expected and actual cost of production, we set our target variable (Cost1) as the difference between the total actual setup and run time and the total expected set up and run time.
box$Machine <- as.character(box$Machine)
i <- sapply(box, is.character)
box[i] <- lapply(box[i], as.factor)
box$Cost1 <- box$`Actual Setup Hours`+box$`Actual Run Hours`-box$`Standard Setup Hours`- box$`Standard Run Hours`
  • Because we are not building a time-series regreesion model, we cannot keep LAST_WORKED (order production date) in time series format. We can extract the months out and call them another variable. We should never include the year when the orders were produced in our dataset, otherwise our model won’t be able to predict the time differences for boxed produced in 2019.
box$prodmonth <- as.numeric(substring(as.character(box$LAST_WORKED),6,7))
box <- box[,-7]
  • Looking at the data summary of our dataset, we found out there were 64 rows in the dataset with missing values in key attributes such as box length and box width. We can never use these observations when we are modeling.
source("data summary.R")

box <- box[-which(is.na(box$`# per Unit`)),]

1.3 Imputation

  • All indicator variables have missing values. However, when a indicator variable is mssing, it means the order does not satisfify a certain criteria. Therefore, “N” (No, as opposed to “Y”) should be imputed for every NAs.
box2 <- box[,22:46]
box1 <- box[,c(1:21,47,48)]
i <- sapply(box2, is.factor)
box2[i] <- lapply(box2[i], as.character)
for (i in 1:25) {
  box2[which(is.na(box2[,i])),i]<- "N"
}
i <- sapply(box2, is.character)
box2[i] <- lapply(box2[i], as.factor)
box <- cbind(box1,box2)

After this is done, we found out the variable SNOW2SLIDES only has one factor level. Therefore it should not be included in our model.

box <- box %>% select(-`Snow 2 Sides`)
  • There are also 19811 NAs in CuttingDie. Unlike the indicator variables, we cannot simply impute an “N” here. These missing values were due to data not collected. We decided to impute “UN” (unknown) for all mssing values in CuttingDie
box$`Cutting Die #` <- as.character(box$`Cutting Die #`)
box$`Cutting Die #`[which(is.na(box$`Cutting Die #`))] <- "UN"
box$`Cutting Die #` <- as.factor(box$`Cutting Die #`)
  • There were 6717 missing values in “# of Ink” and “% of Ink”. Because we asked Casey that day, we are certain that when the two fields are missing, the boxes are not printed. So, we imputed 0s for missing “# of Ink” and “% of Ink”.
library(tidyverse)
box.nums <- box %>% select_if(is.numeric) 
box.cats <- select_if(box,negate(is.numeric))
box.nums$`# of Inks`[which(is.na(box.nums$`# of Inks`))]<-0
box.nums$`% of Ink Coverage`[which(is.na(box.nums$`% of Ink Coverage`))]<-0
boxFinal <- cbind(box.nums,box.cats)

1.4 Collasping Factor Levels

1.4.1 Style

library(data.table)
summ_Style <- data.frame(unclass(summary(boxFinal$Style)),check.names = FALSE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
summ_Style <- as.data.frame(setDT(summ_Style, keep.rownames = TRUE)[])
colnames(summ_Style) <- c("Styles","Frequency")

library(ggplot2)
Frq_Style <- ggplot()+
geom_bar(aes(x=reorder(Styles,Frequency),y=Frequency),data=summ_Style,stat="identity",fill="#1F77B4")+
geom_text(aes(x=reorder(Styles,Frequency),y=Frequency,label=Frequency),hjust=0.03,color="#4D7EBF",data=summ_Style,size=4)+
theme_bw()+coord_flip(ylim=c(0,13500))+scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(0,13500,by=1500))+
ylab("Frequency")+xlab("Styles")+
ggtitle("Frequency of Factor Levels--Styles")+
theme(plot.title = element_text(size=7.5,face="bold",hjust = 0.5),panel.grid.major = element_blank())
Frq_Style

 

Based on the graph, we would like to collaspe the fatcor levels of “Style” so that the frequency of each level is greater than 10% of the total number of observations in the dataset. Our model will predict better if this is done. To make it happen, we combined all RSCL-related factor levels (RSCL,RSCL-DC,RSCL-BID) into one big level. Similarly, we combined all RSCMD related factors (RSCMD1,RSCMD2,RSCMD3) and all RSCW related factors (RSCW, RSCW-DC,RSCW-BID,RSCWXF) into one big factor level—we renamed the level RSC. All remaining factor levels are grouped into another factor level, named OTH (others).

boxFinal$Style <- recode_factor(boxFinal$Style, "FOLL"="OTH", "FOLW"="OTH","FOL"="OTH", 
                                "HSCL"="OTH","HSCW"="OTH","RSCM"="RSC","RSCW"="RSC","HSC"="OTH",
                                "HSCL-DC"="OTH","HSCL2UP"="OTH","HSCW-DC"="OTH",
                                "RSCL-BID"="RSCL", "RSCL-DC"="RSCL", "RSCMD1"="RSC",
                                  "RSCMD2"="RSC","RSCMD3"="RSC","RSCW-BID"="RSC","RSCW-DC"="RSC",
                                "RSCWXF"="RSC","TUBELFLANGED"="OTH", "SPECIAL BOX"="OTH","D/C"="OTH")

 

1.4.2 CuttingDie

 

Apparently, there are a ton of factor levels. Even worse, some factor levels only have 1 or 2 occurences. If we don’t collaspe them, the degrees of freedom will be significantly increased when we build our model due to the number of dummy variables. Our model will be overfitt. Theefore, we decided to combine these factor levels by grouping everything except for UN (“unknown”) and CR12152C into a big factor level.

boxFinal$`Cutting Die #` <- as.character(boxFinal$`Cutting Die #`)
boxFinal$`Cutting Die #`[which(boxFinal$`Cutting Die #` != "CR12152C" & boxFinal$`Cutting Die #` != "UN")] <- "Others"
boxFinal$`Cutting Die #` <- as.factor(boxFinal$`Cutting Die #`)

 

1.4.3 Grade

Similar to CuttingDie, Grade also has over 100 different factor levels.We decided to combine these factor levels by the first 3-4 letters of the gradeof boxes used during production (In Grade, the first 3-4 letters represent the strength of the board. We don’t really care if the board is SFI certified or not).

boxtest <-boxFinal
boxtest$Grade <- as.character(boxtest$Grade )
grade <- unique(as.factor(str_replace_all(substring(boxtest$Grade,1,4),"[^[:alnum:]]", "")))
for(i in 1:length(grade)) {
sch <- as.character(grade[i])
index <- startsWith(boxtest$Grade,sch)
boxtest$Grade[index] <- sch
}
boxtest$Grade <- as.factor(boxtest$Grade )

 

There are still too many factor levels, even after we collasped them according to the first 4 letters of the Grade. We will collaspe them further based on the number of occurences.

boxtest$Grade <- recode_factor(boxtest$Grade, "ROCK"="48C", "200B"="200", "200C"="200",
                               "26B"="26", "26C"="26","275B"="275", "275C"="275","29B"="29",
                               "29C"="29", "44B"="44", "44C"="44", "44K"="44","55C"="55",
                               "55EB"="55","32B"="32","32C"="32","32E"="32")
boxtest$Grade <- recode_factor(boxtest$Grade, "26"="OTH","29"="OTH","55"="OTH","250C"="OTH",
                               "350B"="OTH", "400B"="OTH", "40C"="OTH", "450B"="OTH","48BC"="OTH",
                               "51BC"="OTH","71BC"="OTH", "82BC"="OTH","Non"="OTH","Pre"="OTH",
                               "V3C"="OTH","275"="OTH","44"="40","48C"="40")
boxFinal <- boxtest

 

1.4.4 Flute and Product Code

Flute and Product Code has only 3 levels, but “Glued 1 3/8” only has several occurences. We decided to merge it into “Glued”. Same for Product Code

boxFinal$Flute <- recode_factor(boxFinal$Flute, "BC"="B", "E"="B","EB"="B")
boxFinal$`Glue Joint` <- recode_factor(boxFinal$`Glue Joint`, "Glued 1 3/8\""="Glued")
boxFinal$`Product Code` <- recode_factor(boxFinal$`Product Code`, "MARTI"="WRDFG")

 

1.5 Target Variable Transformation

Our target variable is extremely right skewed.

ggplot() + geom_density(aes(x=Cost1,y=..scaled..),data=boxFinal,fill="#4D7EBF") +
  theme_bw()+
scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(0,280,by=20))+ scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(0,1,0.1))+
ylab("Frequency")+xlab("Difference between Actual and Expected total Time")+
ggtitle("Distribution of Difference in Total Time")+
theme(plot.title = element_text(size=8,face="bold",hjust = 0.5),panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
      text = element_text(size=10))

 

Before we transform our target, we would like to create two other target variables: CostRun and CostSet. CostRun is the difference between Actaul Run time and expected Run time, while CostSet is the difference between Actual Setup time and expected setup time. We will build models for these three target variable independently.

boxFinal$CostSet <- boxFinal$`Actual Setup Hours`- boxFinal$`Standard Setup Hours`
boxFinal$CostRun <- boxFinal$`Actual Run Hours`- boxFinal$`Standard Run Hours`
boxFinal <- boxFinal[,-c(1:4)]

 

To eliminate the skewness of our target variable, we decided to perform logarithm transformation. A normal distribution is required if we want to build a linear regression model. It is not required if we are building a tree model. That is why we are keeping both our log-transformed target varibales and target variables that have not been transformed in our dataset.

boxFinal$Cost1log <- log10(boxFinal$Cost1 + 1 - min(boxFinal$Cost1))
boxFinal$CostSetlog <- log10(boxFinal$CostSet + 1 - min(boxFinal$CostSet))
boxFinal$CostRunlog <- log10(boxFinal$CostRun + 1 - min(boxFinal$CostRun))

1.7 Multicollinearity

Eventually, we chacked to see if there are any significant multicollinearity between the variables in our dataset.

library(corrplot)
M<-cor(box.nums)
corrplot(M,method = "number", number.cex = 0.6)

 

It looks like there are none significant multicollinearity between the variables.

 

1.8 Training/Validation Partitioning

We then devided our dataset into training and validation partitions. Some modeling methods require a smaller training data, while others require a laeger training data size. We would make 75% of the total observations our training data.

set.seed(13)
index<-sample(1:nrow(box), size=round(0.75*nrow(box)))
training <- box[index,]
validation <- box[-index,]

 

2. Modeling

Before we even start to model, lets figure out what could be the primary cost driver:  

From the graph above, we can tell Machine type plays a significant role in determining the difference between actual and expected time. Machine 310 seems to be the slower machine and the major cost driver.
